📌 Introduction
Bellabeat is a technology company focused on women’s wellness.
This project analyzes users’ physical activity, sleep patterns, and daily behaviors to identify habits, inconsistencies, and opportunities to improve overall well‑being.

The analysis answers key questions such as:

What are users’ general habits?

What sleep and activity patterns emerge?

What factors influence rest?

What recommendations can improve wellness?

Tools used:

MySQL → data cleaning, transformation, analysis

Excel → initial CSV inspection

Tableau → final visualizations

The project demonstrates skills in SQL, data cleaning, modeling, documentation, and insight generation.

🧹 Data Preparation & Cleaning
Cleaning goals
Unify activity and sleep tables

Fix date formats

Remove duplicates

Create new analytical fields

Ensure consistency across daily records

Key join query
sql
SELECT
    a.id AS user_id,
    a.activity_date AS date,
    a.total_steps,
    a.calories,
    s.minutes_asleep,
    s.minutes_restless,
    s.minutes_awake,
    s.total_minutes_in_bed
FROM DailyActivity a
INNER JOIN SleepDaily s
    ON a.user_id = s.user_id
    AND a.activity_date = s.date_sleep;
This final table was saved as SleepActivityClean, the base for all analyses.

📈 Analysis 1: Physical Activity
Query
sql
SELECT
    AVG(total_steps) AS avg_steps,
    AVG(calories) AS avg_calories
FROM SleepActivityClean;
Findings
Users average 9,142 steps/day → moderate activity

Average calories burned: 2,467/day → consistent with an active lifestyle

😴 Analysis 2: Sleep Overview
Query
sql
SELECT
    AVG(minutes_asleep) AS avg_sleep,
    AVG(total_minutes_in_bed) AS avg_total_minutes_in_bed
FROM SleepActivityClean;
Findings
Average sleep: 395 min (6.6 hours) → insufficient

Time in bed: 428 min (7.1 hours) → low sleep efficiency

🔗 Analysis 3: Activity–Sleep Relationship
Query
sql
SELECT
    AVG(total_steps) AS avg_steps,
    AVG(minutes_asleep) AS avg_sleep
FROM SleepActivityClean;
Findings
More steps do not guarantee better sleep

Very active users sleep less (fatigue/overtraining)

Sedentary users sleep more but with lower quality

⏱️ Analysis 4: Insufficient Sleep (<7 hours)
Query
sql
SELECT
    user_id,
    COUNT(*) AS total_days,
    SUM(CASE WHEN minutes_asleep < 420 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS low_sleep_days,
    ROUND(
        SUM(CASE WHEN minutes_asleep < 420 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) * 100.0 / COUNT(*), 2
    ) AS low_sleep_percentage
FROM SleepActivityClean
GROUP BY user_id
ORDER BY low_sleep_percentage DESC;
Findings
5 users sleep <7 hours on more than 50% of days

Indicates chronic insufficient rest

Worst days: Monday, Thursday, Friday → stress + social factors

📊 Analysis 5: Overall Dataset Trends
Global averages
sql
SELECT
    AVG(total_steps),
    AVG(calories),
    AVG(minutes_asleep),
    AVG(total_minutes_in_bed)
FROM SleepActivityClean;
Variability
sql
SELECT
    STDDEV(total_steps),
    STDDEV(calories),
    STDDEV(minutes_asleep)
FROM SleepActivityClean;
Activity distribution
sql
SELECT
    CASE
        WHEN total_steps < 5000 THEN 'Down'
        WHEN total_steps BETWEEN 5000 AND 9999 THEN 'Reasonable'
        ELSE 'High'
    END AS activity_level,
    COUNT(*) AS days
FROM SleepActivityClean
GROUP BY activity_level;
Sleep distribution
sql
SELECT
    CASE
        WHEN minutes_asleep < 429 THEN 'low_sleep'
        ELSE 'good_sleep'
    END AS sleep_category,
    COUNT(*) AS days
FROM SleepActivityClean
GROUP BY sleep_category;
Key findings
High variability → very different lifestyles

Moderate/high activity dominate

Sleep quality inconsistent

Sleeping more ≠ sleeping better

